Here is a text, which is negative: {{there is definitely not enough room in that part of the venue.}} Here is a rewrite of the text, which is positive: {{the venue has enough space.}}
The latter is more natural for me, but does the first rewrite seem correct? I'm asking not only about formal correctness of writing it that way, but also about the logic of such thinking.

A:

The rewrite is wrong. Your original version is correct:
{{there is definitely not enough room in that part of the venue.}}

The main rule that guides the process of rewording is the "is always true" rule.
{{The venue has enough space.}}

The "is always true" rule says "if a context like this always applies to a sentence in a specific way (in this case, as an assertion), then the sentence makes perfect sense and is fine the way it is".
So in your case "that is always true" applies to "that is not enough room" as part of an assertion. When you state the sentence as an assertion it is valid, and when you state it as an implication it is not valid.
{{The venue has enough room.}}

