This page describes the syntax for the syntax of the templating language in the {{{..}}} tag block. Template tag blocks were introduced to make it easier to create structured data. This was considered as an alternative of the more verbose programming languages.

The syntax for templates is essentially the same as for HTML, with the following minor exceptions

Template tag blocks are delimited by {{{ and }}}, and have no other tags. The {$name} tag is a special tag, which represents the result of the expression stored in the name, which is defined when it is first declared. It is the result of the most recently evaluated expression. Variables and macros (noted in the text below) have the same scope as the tag, unless otherwise noted.

A template has the following types:

Template blocks: text that does not contain any tag or sub-template;

Tag blocks: text that contains only {{{ and }}}, and does not contain either variables or macros;

